    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "[The documentation](http://cython.readthedocs.io/en/latest/src/userguide/language_basics.html) strongly implies that the include statement can be used anywhere:\r\n\r\n> The contents of the included file should begin at an indentation level of zero, and will be treated as though they were indented to the level of the include statement that is including the file.\r\n\r\nBut this is not the case:\r\n\r\n```\r\nError compiling Cython file:\r\n------------------------------------------------------------\r\n...\r\ndef f():\r\n    include \"test2.py\"\r\n   ^\r\n------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\r\ntest.pyx:2:4: include statement not allowed here\r\n```\r\n\r\nPrevious reports on mailing list: [here](http://cython-users.narkive.com/LwSHQgu5/include-statement-only-at-module-level-contrary-to-documentation) and [here](https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/cython-users/FWgvQB_zjFY).\r\n\r\nIdeally this restriction would be removed, but until then, the documentation should be corrected.",
    "closed_at": "2018-03-04T17:58:39Z",
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "\"indented\" does not imply \"inside of a function\". I've clarified the paragraph.",
